<dl id="n10035i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10035i">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10035i"> 35(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Joshua&apos;s summertime <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10035i"><li>FW 53.22 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n10035i">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n10035i">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10035i">MS BL 47472-230</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:226 <a name="cd5" href="../../ff/fdra/cda.htm#cd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/cd5.htm#n10035i">Draft: I.3&sect;1.5</a>/2.5/3.5</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>SUMMER TIME</mark>. SOME OBJECTIONS TO THE MEASURE. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Speaking of the objections to the proposal, on the ground that it was an interference with Divine Providence, and was contrary to the rule laid down in the Book of <mark>Joshua</mark>, Sir Kingsley Wood disclaimed any idea of standing as a presumptuous Joshua. It was far removed from his intention to say: &ldquo;Sun, stand thou still upon Gideon, and thou, Moon, in the valley of Ajalon.&rdquo; He did not propose to tamper with the dispensations of Providence, or with the movement of the heavenly bodies. <small> <a name="IT12apr24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#IT12apr24"><cite title="source">Irish Times</cite></a> (12 April 1924) 6/7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
